			"note": "<div><br></div><div>(Reduced) Row Echelon Form -- a canonical form that we can transform a matrix into, which is incredibly useful for solving numerous problems.</div><div><br></div><div>Definitions:&nbsp;</div><div>A matrix is in *row echelon form* if:</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; (1) all zero rows are at the bottom (rows consisting of all zeros)</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; (2) the first nonzero entry in each row (the leading entry) is in a column to the left of any leading entries below it. &nbsp; &nbsp;(ugh)</div><div><br></div><div>Show several examples to understand what this means.</div><div><br></div><div>A matrix is in REDUCED row echelon form if:</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;(1) its in row echelon form</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;(2) each leading entry is a 1</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;(3) all other entries in each column with a leading 1 are 0.</div><div><br></div>"
		},
		{
			"id": "e78d8963-2852-445f-9414-8cf5f81964a5",
			"note": "<div><br></div>WHY? &nbsp;<div><br></div><div>1. There are (fast) algorithms to \"transform\" a matrix into echelon form.</div><div><br></div><div>2. If you rewrite a system of linear equations in terms of matrices, and \"tranform\" to echelon form (for some definition of \"transform\"), then consider the equations corresponding to the result, the solution is easy to read off.... and is exactly the same as the set of solutions to the original problem.</div>"
