		{
			"id": "7b7d5f87-ea66-4acf-b051-c2116ee42bd7",
			"note": "HOW?<div><br></div><div>Here are the allowed operations, i.e., definition of \"transform\":</div><div><br></div><div>1. Interchange two rows &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div>2. Multiply a row by a nonzero constant</div><div>3. Add a multiple of a row to another row</div><div><br></div><div>NOTICE: -- this is *exactly* what you do when you solve a system of linear equations directly by hand. &nbsp; So it should be really easy to remember. &nbsp;These are exactly the operations that preserve the set of solutions (convince yourself of this).&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>FACT: Using the above 3 operations, you can transform any matrix into reduced row echelon form. &nbsp; &nbsp;One straightforward way to do this, is the following:</div><div><br></div><div>1. Choose any nonzero entry in the first column (or skip that column if it is zero and move to the next one).</div><div>2. Rescale the corresponding row so that leading entry is 1.</div><div>3. Add multiples of that row to all the the rows so that their leading entry is 0.</div><div>4. Swap that row with the first row.</div><div>5. Do exactly the same thing again, but with the next column.</div><div><br></div><div>That's it. &nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>The really, really shocking thing is that it doesn't matter how you make the choice in step 1, you'll always end up with the same answer in the end. This is a kind of like how integers factor uniquely as a product of prime numbers.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>NOTE: for the purpose of solving linear equations, you might reduce to just echelon form (not reduced echelon form), which is of course not unique.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div>"
